Rated operating pressure: 0.75 MPa; Rated flow: 3 L/s;
Expansion rate: ≥6;
Jet distance: wet foam ≥25 m, dry foam ≥22 m.

ce:section.ce:para:
The experimental evolution process is illustrated in Fig. 4
                        . Time began when the electric heater was activated. The slight explosion sound and the sudden rise in battery pack temperature indicated that the first TR happened at 2368 s. It took longer to trigger TR, probably because the cooling system of the pack decreased the heating efficiency of the heater. Subsequently, there was continuous TR. During this time, the battery pack emitted white smoke. At 2773 s, flames appeared in the undercarriage of the vehicle along with a large amount of smoke (see Fig. 5
                        ).

The vehicle can be divided into four sections: the battery pack, engine compartment, trunk, and passenger compartment (see Fig. 6
                        ). The passenger compartment is highly flammable. The fire spread along the chassis and body after the battery pack caught fire. Following three jet flame, a flame formed around the right rear wheel. Hot smoke permeated into the passenger compartment through the gap in the rear seat and through cracks in the doors (see Fig. 7
                        ). The flame spread from the right rear wheel to the trunk and wrapped around the car's right rear. As the windows were open during the experiment, there was no significant temperature change in the cabin. During this period the maximum temperature measured outside the car was 155.2 °C. It can be seen that in the initial stages of an EV fire, the combustion behavior has a limited impact on the cabin and surroundings; however, a jet fire is a danger that requires more attention.

According to the infrared images, the TR occurred constantly after the fire blanket was covered (see Fig. 12
                        ). During this time, white gases escaped from the battery and sometimes produced visible flash-fire-like flames (see Fig. 13
                        ). White gas is thought to be electrolyte vapor, CxHy, CO, and H2 from the TR batteries. A previous study determined the explosion limit of the gas emitted from TR batteries [33]. After a while, the gases gradually faded and became barely visible.

In the experiment, the water mist was used 78 s after re-ignition. After the implementation of the water mist, smoke was blown to diffuse. At this point, the black smoke was mixed with the white steam, and its color became lighter (see Fig. 14
                        ). Under the kinetic energy of water mist, the inclination of the fire flow changed, and a “flare-up” lasting several seconds occurred at the instant of first contact with the water mist. The temperature trend chart also shows that at the start of using the water mist, the temperature increased steeply (see Fig. 15
                        ). The fine water mist may have initially intensified combustion. The water mist brings additional air into the flame zone [36]. Conversely, the water mist increases the concentration of 


                                 OH
                                 −


                         radicals in the flame zone, thereby enhancing the chemical reaction [37]. The cooling effect of the fine water mist then kicked in, with a cooling rate of −3.1 °C/s on average.
